english:
  title: Postscript to Poems on the Hall of Three Virtues
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Byeok family of the Northern court, perceiving the Yuan Dynasty's descent into chaos, relocated their household to the Eastern Land, where they were enfeoffed and drew stipends throughout their lives, and their descendants were preserved. Such was the clarity of their wisdom.

    They had four sons. The eldest rose to the position of prime minister, and when dispatched repeatedly as envoy to the Ming court, his responses were so keen and eloquent that the Great Progenitor repeatedly praised him. He rendered service to our realm and upon his death was posthumously titled Minister Mun-jeong. The second was a man of generous nature and dignified bearing, also ascending to the rank of Chancellor. The third and fourth both possessed talent and achieved high office. I held them all in friendship, and with Minister Mun-jeong in particular, I served together in court with ever-deepening affection.

    When Mun-jeong once recounted the deeds of his forebears at the Hall of Three Virtues and recited the commemorative verses composed by various scholars, I listened with reverence and admiration. Upon reading the family history written by the erudite Ou-yang, I found the record of the three virtues set forth in detail.

    The Regional Commander risked all to suppress rebellion for the nation, refusing to yield even as his strength failed, and appearing as a guardian spirit thereafter to encourage the troops—such was the loyalty of a true minister. His widow remained steadfast in her vow and unflinching in her virtue—such was the chastity of a true wife. The General Administrator, at merely ten years of age, severed his own flesh to heal his mother—such was the filial devotion of a true son. Within one household, the three virtues converged. Their descendants, blessed by this accumulated grace, whenever they entered the examination halls, rose without fail to office. Scholars have commemorated this fortune in verse, writing of "six cassia branches before the Hall of Three Virtues"—thus celebrating their glory.

    In our eastern tradition, when three brothers of one family pass the civil service examination together, it is accounted a rare blessing, and rewards are bestowed upon their mother. That Minister Mun-jeong and his two younger brothers ascended simultaneously testifies that the fruits of accumulated virtue never cease.

    In the summer of the year Imsin, the youngest brother, the Keeper of Records, came to me saying: "Our family's compositions praising the Hall of Three Virtues have been scattered and nearly lost. Fearing their utter disappearance, I have gathered the surviving pieces into one volume, and wish to request writings from the learned gentlemen of the realm. I begin with you." I accepted, yet lingered for months due to my inadequate skill. He visited repeatedly with ever greater deference. Apologizing for my incapacity, I then spoke thus:

    "The great human relationships are ordained by Heaven. The minister serves his lord, the wife her husband, the child his parents—each has their proper role. In ordinary times one must fulfill what is right; in times of trial one must not abandon what one has sworn to uphold. When both are perfectly maintained, virtue is complete. Yet those throughout history remembered for virtue were not renowned in ordinary times but in times of trial. For in ordinary times all behave well, but in trial few hold firm. Only after facing adversity and distinctly revealing one's righteousness, standing out from the common multitude, can one truly be called virtuous. This cannot be accomplished without clarity in propriety, indifference to profit and harm, and a spirit unwavering. Therefore, those who perfectly embody the way of minister, child, and spouse, and are remembered for virtue, appear scarcely once in an age.

    Now your household has produced three such exemplars in succession, and their glory fills the records without limit. Surely your descendants shall flourish and spread throughout all lands, perpetuating excellence from generation to generation, transmitting the enduring blessings to ages without end."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Hall of Three Virtues' (Samjeoldang) refers to a commemorative structure honoring three members of the Byeok family—the Regional Commander (loyalty), his widow (chastity), and the General Administrator (filial piety)—each embodying a cardinal virtue during times of upheaval.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'six cassia branches' is a poetic reference to familial prosperity and literary accomplishment, alluding to the family's success in the civil service examinations.
  - key: ''
    value: The year Imsin corresponds to 1452 in the Gregorian calendar, during the reign of King Munjong of Joseon.
